                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d286">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">835.5151/431 Suppl.: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cox</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-29T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 29, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. Consulate General’s telegram of April 17, 9 a.m.,<note n="9" xml:id="d286fn9"
                        >Not printed.</note> and Department’s telegram 36, April 25, 11 a.m. In any
                    further discussions of the recent exchange decree which you may have with the
                    Minister for Foreign Affairs, please inquire regarding the truth of the report
                    that a surcharge of 20 percent will be added to all bids for Argentine
                    Government contracts received from countries with which Argentina has an
                    unfavorable trade balance. In case this report is founded, you may say that this
                    Government hopes that American firms will have the opportunity to bid for
                    Argentine Government contracts on equal terms with other foreign firms.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
